It is actually fairly common to hear older Poles comment that they “haven’t heard of a divorce” in the last 30 years, not out of denial but because such an event was practically unheard of in the country during most of the 20th century. The Polish lira also had the ability to buy a lot of basic products in general and all kinds of beauty products, which led to cosmetics stores proliferating across the entire country. No woman could do without a good lipstick – ideally red – a little blush and eyebrow pencil. Every Polish woman knew just as well, if not better, than Polish men how to define success. We were taught that if you are a woman then your number one goal is to hold her own in society and beat men at their own game, although this belief only took root fairly recently.

In many ways being young in Poland meant a perfect preparation for survival in the harsh business world, as we had to fight for recognition day in and day out. We were well-educated, culturally savvy and cheerful. The sheer enthusiasm and optimism saw us through nearly any hardship.

The second part of this true story covers life in Poland in the fall of 1989.
